I actually believe you.

01:02:08.000 --> 01:02:09.620
AUDIENCE: I'll ask
you my question after.

01:02:09.620 --> 01:02:10.286
MIKE POSNER: No.

01:02:10.286 --> 01:02:10.930
I believe you.

01:02:10.930 --> 01:02:12.250
I really wanted to make a joke.

01:02:12.250 --> 01:02:17.790
But typically, how
that stuff works is

01:02:17.790 --> 01:02:23.450
it's largely based on royalties.

01:02:23.450 --> 01:02:27.940
So you get a percentage,
depending on how many people

01:02:27.940 --> 01:02:29.230
wrote the song.

01:02:29.230 --> 01:02:33.340
I'm a big proponent of, if
there are four guys in the room,

01:02:33.340 --> 01:02:35.230
you just split it even.

01:02:35.230 --> 01:02:38.500
Sometimes people get into this
thing where, I wrote 30 lines,

01:02:38.500 --> 01:02:43.120
and you wrote 29, so I
should get this much.

01:02:43.120 --> 01:02:45.370
That always gets icky to me.

01:02:45.370 --> 01:02:47.050
I like to just do it even.

01:02:47.050 --> 01:02:51.070
And so basically, you
get paid a percentage

01:02:51.070 --> 01:02:54.816
of whatever money comes in.

01:02:54.816 --> 01:02:56.440
For producers, it's
a little different.

01:02:56.440 --> 01:02:59.760
A producer, depending
on who it is,

01:02:59.760 --> 01:03:01.840
gets an advance,
which means they

01:03:01.840 --> 01:03:04.720
get paid the money upfront.

01:03:04.720 --> 01:03:09.250
And then as the money
comes in, the other person

01:03:09.250 --> 01:03:11.110
gets that advance paid
back, and then they

01:03:11.110 --> 01:03:13.360
get the profits after that.

01:03:13.360 --> 01:03:19.210
So advance for
producers can range.

01:03:19.210 --> 01:03:23.770
If it's your first beat you're
ever selling, typically, going

01:03:23.770 --> 01:03:26.462
rate is, like, $5,000, I think.

01:03:26.462 --> 01:03:27.920
You'd probably know
better than me.

01:03:27.920 --> 01:03:30.580
But a new producer--

01:03:30.580 --> 01:03:33.310
$5,000 to $10,000
would be an advance.

01:03:33.310 --> 01:03:36.000
And then I don't know
what the high end is now.

01:03:39.130 --> 01:03:41.950
Back in the days when people
were buying more music,

01:03:41.950 --> 01:03:43.160
like Scott Storch--

01:03:43.160 --> 01:03:45.970
these guys sell a
track for $1 million.

01:03:45.970 --> 01:03:48.967
But I think that's gone down
because people buy less music.

01:03:48.967 --> 01:03:49.800
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

01:03:49.800 --> 01:03:50.914
Now, my question.

01:03:50.914 --> 01:03:51.580
MIKE POSNER: OK.

01:03:51.580 --> 01:03:52.744
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:03:52.744 --> 01:03:53.410
MIKE POSNER: OK.

01:03:53.410 --> 01:03:53.951
AUDIENCE: OK.

01:03:53.951 --> 01:03:56.050
So at the beginning
of the talk, you

01:03:56.050 --> 01:04:01.060
mentioned how maybe global
warming is something really

01:04:01.060 --> 01:04:02.650
important, but maybe
it doesn't really

01:04:02.650 --> 01:04:04.816
matter because we're getting
in the way of something

01:04:04.816 --> 01:04:05.410
much larger.

01:04:05.410 --> 01:04:07.368
So then, when you think
about things like that,

01:04:07.368 --> 01:04:09.850
then how do you decide
what really matters?

01:04:09.850 --> 01:04:10.600
MIKE POSNER: Yeah.

01:04:10.600 --> 01:04:13.330
I'm not sure anything does.

01:04:13.330 --> 01:04:15.250
There are things definitely
that matter to me.

01:04:15.250 --> 01:04:18.070
Like, my mom matters to me.

01:04:18.070 --> 01:04:19.720
But there is that
in the background,

01:04:19.720 --> 01:04:23.350
like why does it matter that
your mom matters to you?

01:04:23.350 --> 01:04:27.700
If I just cut her off,
which I never would do,

01:04:27.700 --> 01:04:30.920
does that matter in the
great scheme of things?

01:04:30.920 --> 01:04:33.880
And the answer is we don't know.

01:04:33.880 --> 01:04:36.940
We don't have perspective
enough to tell.

01:04:40.681 --> 01:04:41.180
Yeah.

01:04:41.180 --> 01:04:43.760
If we had, like, a God
perspective, we could see.

01:04:49.490 --> 01:04:51.650
The Bible says, that thou
shall not kill, right?

01:04:51.650 --> 01:04:53.110
It sounds reasonable, right?

01:04:53.110 --> 01:04:54.520
I don't kill people.

01:04:54.520 --> 01:04:59.450
But what if, like, the person
was about to kill two people?

01:04:59.450 --> 01:05:01.540
Then, is it OK?

01:05:01.540 --> 01:05:06.087
So these things get
icky really quickly.

01:05:06.087 --> 01:05:07.170
And somebody would say no.

01:05:07.170 --> 01:05:10.830
But what if they were about
to kill a million people?

01:05:10.830 --> 01:05:13.445
I don't know.

01:05:13.445 --> 01:05:14.750
It's very nuanced.

01:05:14.750 --> 01:05:17.709
And we don't have the
perspective to see what--

01:05:17.709 --> 01:05:19.250
AUDIENCE: So does
that get in the way

01:05:19.250 --> 01:05:20.564
of your happiness every day?

01:05:20.564 --> 01:05:21.980
If you're making
decisions, do you

01:05:21.980 --> 01:05:23.150
think about it broadly like--

01:05:23.150 --> 01:05:24.066
MIKE POSNER: At times.

01:05:24.066 --> 01:05:26.074
There's an EB White quote
that says, "I wake up

01:05:26.074 --> 01:05:28.490
in the morning, and I don't
know whether to save the world

01:05:28.490 --> 01:05:29.600
or savor it.

01:05:29.600 --> 01:05:32.480
This makes it hard
to start the day."

01:05:32.480 --> 01:05:33.170
And yeah.

01:05:33.170 --> 01:05:34.790
I feel that sometimes.

01:05:34.790 --> 01:05:36.940
But it's waves.

01:05:36.940 --> 01:05:39.450
Sometimes I go, well, I'm just
going to play my guitar a lot

01:05:39.450 --> 01:05:41.150
today.

01:05:41.150 --> 01:05:41.900
AUDIENCE: Awesome.

01:05:41.900 --> 01:05:42.400
